    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>LEAD: To the Editor:</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>LEAD: To the Editor:</p>
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Michael Oppenheimer and Daniel J. Dudek (''Protecting the Ozone Layer,'' Op-Ed, Aug. 6) state that ''Chlorofluorocarbons are widely used in refrigerators, air conditioners, plastics manufacturing, aerosols and as solvents. This is erroneous for the United States aerosol industry.</p>
        <p>Aerosols produced and marketed in the United States no longer contain chlorofluorocarbons, in compliance with the Environmental Protection Agency's 1978 ban on the use of chlorofluorocarbons as propellants in aerosol spray cans. Only slightly more than 1 percent of aerosols, for essential medicinal uses, are exempt from this ban. RALPH ENGEL  President, Chemical Specialties  Manufacturers Association  Washington, Aug. 16, 1987</p>
      </block>
